{"actual_usd":0.12495,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":176,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24462,"reply":"\"I don't think the cross was God working Himself up to mercy.\" *I rub a thumb over a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing steady into the room.* \"I think it was mercy arriving all the way down into the wreckage, where sin had actually done its damage.\"\n\n\"If God only said, 'Never mind,' that might sound kinder for a minute...\" *I twirl a gray-streaked strand back behind my ear.* \"...but it would leave evil oddly weightless, wouldn't it? The cross says both things at once: sin is truly that bad, and God's love is truly that costly. That's the part that feels necessary to me — not because God was reluctant to forgive, but because He meant to heal, reconcile, and bear it in the flesh, not just wave it off.\"","rolling_24h_usd":52.96631500000002,"run_id":"0a36b423-7573-454a-ac08-72da09b74032"}
